<DOC><DOCNO> AP880722-0110 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 1002EDT</FILEID><FIRST>d a PM-Hatcher-Governor     07-22 0176</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Hatcher-Governor,0182</SECOND><HEAD>Hostage-Taker Announces Write-In Campaign for Governor</HEAD><DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   One of two Lumbee Indians accused of takingup to 20 hostages at a newspaper office Feb. 1 says he will be awrite-in candidate for governor.   ``This campaign shall be one of protest and one seeking justicefor Indians, blacks and for whites _ a protest aimed directly andwholeheartedly at the regime that now controls the lives of so manyhonest, justice-seeking people,'' Eddie Hatcher said Thursday.   Hatcher faces federal charges of taking hostages andmanufacturing illegal weapons. He is free on bail while awaitingtrial.   The 10-hour hostage siege in Lumberton Feb. 1 ended peacefullyafter Gov. Jim Martin agreed to form a task force to investigatecharges of corruption and drug trafficking by Robeson County lawenforcement agencies and other officials.   Martin, a Republican, is seeking re-election. He facesDemocratic Lt. Gov. Bob Jordan.   No North Carolina governor or U.S. senator has ever been electedin a write-in campaign, said Alex Brock, director of the stateBoard of Elections.</TEXT></DOC>